<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos myrtifolia </i>is an erect to spreading evergreen shrub that lacks a lignotuber. Seeds collect in the duff and ground in a seed bank as stones as plants age. <i>A. myrtifolia </i>appears be as much dependent upon fire as special soil conditions associated with it. Tree seedlings are establishing in canopy openings of older stands. <br/>
<br/>
The <i>Arctostaphylos myrtifolia </i>alliance occurs primarily on outcrops of the Ione Formation, which has highly acidic, infertile paleosols with high levels of aluminum that were produced under subtropical or tropical climates (USFWS 1999). Holzman and Meyer (2004) mapped the alliance and associated vegetation types, and found that it covers only 484 ha. Only 5% of the alliance occurs on public land. The largest and least impacted stands occur in the Dry Creek and Willow Creek drainages between State Routes 18 and 104. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos myrtifolia </i>is a CNPS list 1B.2 plant. Other rare plants, <i>Eriogonum apricum </i>var. <i>apricum, E. a. </i>var. <i>prostratum </i>(CNPS list 1B.1 plants), <i>Horkelia parryi </i>(a CNPS list 1B.2 plant), and <i>Helianthemum suffrutescens </i>(a CNPS list 3.2 plant) grow in this alliance. <br/>
<br/>
Gankin and Major (1964) discuss the acidic soils and relatively moderated climate for this part of the Sierra Nevada foothills. This manzanita grows due east of the Golden Gate. Its closest relatives occur in the maritime chaparral (the forms of <i>A. nummularia, A. uva-ursi</i>), suggesting paleoecological ties to the flora of the Central Coast (Boykin et al. 2005). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
