    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fb). Stands occur over a 9500-ha area in western Amador Co. and a very small portion of Calaveras Co. (Holzman and Meyer 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos myrtifolia </i>habitat contains commercially valuable minerals, and a significant permanent loss of its habitat has occurred. Fifteen surface mines have extracted sand, gravel, gold, kaolinitic clays, lowgrade coal, and other minerals, and seriously continue to threaten the alliance. Roads, highways, and a patchwork of agricultural, commercial, and residential development (Hartwell 2006) also impact the habitat. Diseases, especially a root rot ( <i>Phytophthora cinnamomi</i>), a close relative of the sudden oak death pathogen <i>P. ramorum</i>, are immediate threats to <i>A. myrtifolia </i>(Swiecki and Bernhardt 2003). They are a more serious threat than fire suppression, residential development, or agriculture conversion. Wood and Parker (1988) report shrub density and cover at Apricum Hill Ecological Reserve; a recent study (Holzman and Meyer 2004) found that 30% of <i>A. myrtifolia </i>shrubs had less than half of their crowns with live foliage, mostly due to pathogens. </div>
</div>

    

    

